Reasoning: The paper discusses the tension between highly structured models and highly complex, general-purpose models in theoretical cognitive science, and applies this tension to the field of educational data mining. It specifically compares the performance of deep learning (DKT) and Bayesian knowledge tracing (BKT) in predicting student performance. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science). The paper also discusses natural language processing techniques (such as contextualized trial sequence), which suggests a possible fit with cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, the paper is focused on educational data mining, which suggests a possible fit with cs.EDU (Education).
